logical operators are used to perform logical operations on boolean values or expressions.

There are three main logical operators:

Logical AND (&&): The logical AND operator returns true if both operands are true, otherwise,
it returns false.
Logical OR (||): The logical OR operator returns true if at least one of the operands is true,
otherwise, it returns false.
Logical NOT (!): The logical NOT operator negates the boolean value of its operand.
If the operand is true, it returns false; if the operand is false, it returns true.

Here's a quick summary:

Logical AND (&&):
true && true returns true
true && false returns false
false && true returns false
false && false returns false

Logical OR (||):
true || true returns true
true || false returns true
false || true returns true
false || false returns false

Logical NOT (!):
!true returns false
!false returns true
